---
/**
 * /about — the "who I am" page. Personal-brand identity: the operator behind the
 * tools. Prose is public-safe (the employer is named only by generic descriptor —
 * the safe-export firewall hard-blocks the literal). Identity + socials come from
 * src/data/site.ts; structured data adds a ProfilePage + BreadcrumbList on top of
 * the site-wide Person node in BaseLayout.
 */
import PageLayout from '../../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import Icon from '../../components/Icon.astro';
import { site, socials } from '../../data/site';
import { bySlug } from '../../data/sections';

const section = bySlug.get('about')!;
const origin = new URL(Astro.site!).origin;
const personId = `${origin}/#person`;

const aboutSchema = [
  {
    '@type': 'ProfilePage',
    '@id': `${origin}/about/#profilepage`,
    name: `About ${site.name}`,
    url: `${origin}/about/`,
    description: section.description,
    isPartOf: { '@id': `${origin}/#website` },
    mainEntity: { '@id': personId },
  },
  {
    '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
    '@id': `${origin}/about/#breadcrumb`,
    itemListElement: [
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: `${origin}/` },
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'About', item: `${origin}/about/` },
    ],
  },
];

// Icon per social label (falls back to the external-link arrow).
const socialIcon = (label: string) => {
  const l = label.toLowerCase();
  if (l === 'github') return 'git-branch';
  if (l === 'linkedin') return 'linkedin';
  if (l === 'nextdoor') return 'nextdoor';
  return 'arrow-up-right';
};
---
<PageLayout
  title="About"
  description={section.description}
  image="/og/about.png?v=1"
  schema={aboutSchema}
>
  {/* ── Intro hero ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden border-b border-line">
    <div class="bg-grid bg-grid-fade pointer-events-none absolute inset-0 -z-10 opacity-60"></div>
    <div class="relative mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 pt-20 pb-16 sm:pt-28 sm:pb-24">
      <p class="mono-label">About</p>
      <h1 class="mt-3 max-w-3xl font-display text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink sm:text-5xl">
        The operator who directs AI to build his own software.
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-2xl font-display text-lg leading-relaxed text-cyan">
        I run supply-chain operations — and I direct AI to build the software those operations always needed:
        full-stack, Python to the edge, orchestrated end to end.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-2xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-ink-muted">
        I'm Ian Provencher — a supply-chain operator who's spent years inside the flow of real
        material through real plants, and who now directs AI to build the software that fixes the exact problems that
        flow throws off: full-stack applications, data tooling, and agentic systems, orchestrated end
        to end. Deep domain, real shipped software, and a bias for the working
        tool over the slide deck.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-2xl text-base leading-relaxed text-ink-muted">
        This site is my public workspace — the repos, tools, cron jobs, apps, and architectures behind
        the work, plus the field notes. It renders reviewed, public-safe snapshots of the real
        infrastructure I run; it never re-types it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ── /01 The operator behind it ─────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-16 sm:py-20">
    <p class="flex items-center gap-2.5">
      <span class="section-index">/ 01</span>
      <span class="mono-label">The operator behind it</span>
    </p>
    <div class="mt-6 flex flex-col gap-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-ink-muted">
      <p>
        Years as a supply-chain analyst at a global home-appliance manufacturer — deep inside
        end-to-end operations: the flow of material through real plants and the systems
        that run it, from planning and sourcing to production, logistics, warehousing, and
        engineering. Not adjacent to it, not advising on it from a deck — actually running the parts
        most software is built without ever touching, down to the MRP and BOM mechanics underneath.
      </p>
      <p>
        That's the moat. When the problem is a tangle of planning logic, material constraints, and the
        gaps an ERP left behind, I understand it in operational terms before a single line of code
        exists — so what gets built solves the real problem, not a tidy abstraction of it.
      </p>
      <p>
        And the AI half isn't new. A passion for it ran alongside the operations work the whole way —
        and it's now formally part of my role, helping shape the path, scope, and implementations of
        AI across the company's North America region.
      </p>
      <p class="text-ink">
        Strip the domain away and the job is constant: find the hard, specific, one-off problem nobody
        will build a product for — and ship the exact tool that solves it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ── /02 What I build here ──────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section class="section-band">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-16 sm:py-20">
      <p class="flex items-center gap-2.5">
        <span class="section-index">/ 02</span>
        <span class="mono-label">What I build</span>
      </p>
      <p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-ink-muted">
        I build my own operational software end to end — full-stack apps, tools, cron jobs, and
        architectures that keep a one-person operation running like a much larger one — with AI
        (mostly Claude Code) as the force multiplier. The real estate is private; what you see here is
        the reviewed, public-safe render of it.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-8 grid grid-cols-1 gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <a href="/tools/" class="reveal panel flex items-center gap-3 p-4 transition-colors hover:border-line-2">
          <span class="grid h-9 w-9 shrink-0 place-items-center rounded-lg border border-line bg-surface-2 text-accent"><Icon name="wrench" size={17} /></span>
          <span class="text-sm leading-snug text-ink-muted"><span class="font-medium text-ink">Builds</span> — the software I've shipped</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/architectures/" class="reveal panel flex items-center gap-3 p-4 transition-colors hover:border-line-2">
          <span class="grid h-9 w-9 shrink-0 place-items-center rounded-lg border border-line bg-surface-2 text-cyan"><Icon name="network" size={17} /></span>
          <span class="text-sm leading-snug text-ink-muted"><span class="font-medium text-ink">Architectures</span> — diagrams of the systems</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/cron/" class="reveal panel flex items-center gap-3 p-4 transition-colors hover:border-line-2">
          <span class="grid h-9 w-9 shrink-0 place-items-center rounded-lg border border-line bg-surface-2 text-indigo"><Icon name="timer" size={17} /></span>
          <span class="text-sm leading-snug text-ink-muted"><span class="font-medium text-ink">Cron</span> — the machinery that runs itself</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/command-center/" class="reveal panel flex items-center gap-3 p-4 transition-colors hover:border-line-2">
          <span class="grid h-9 w-9 shrink-0 place-items-center rounded-lg border border-line bg-surface-2 text-cyan"><Icon name="radar" size={17} /></span>
          <span class="text-sm leading-snug text-ink-muted"><span class="font-medium text-ink">Command Center</span> — the console I run it all from</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ── /03 What actually drives me ────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-16 sm:py-20">
    <p class="flex items-center gap-2.5">
      <span class="section-index">/ 03</span>
      <span class="mono-label">What actually drives me</span>
    </p>
    <div class="mt-6 flex flex-col gap-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-ink-muted">
      <p>
        The part that drives me isn't the building — it's the sharing. AI is the biggest leveler small
        business has ever had. The shop running on spreadsheets can have its data turned into a working
        tool today, and own the custom system it runs on tomorrow — no enterprise budget, no license,
        no asking permission.
      </p>
      <p class="text-ink">
        The businesses that harness that won't just keep up; they'll own what they used to buy off the
        shelf. Helping more of them get there is the whole point of
        <a href="https://appliediqsolutions.com" class="name-accent font-semibold" target="_blank" rel="noopener">AppliedIQ Solutions</a>,
        my practice — custom supply-chain software and AI-built operational tools, designed and shipped
        by one operator who's run the floor.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ── Connect ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section class="section-band">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-14 sm:py-16">
      <p class="flex items-center gap-2.5">
        <span class="section-index">/ 04</span>
        <span class="mono-label">Connect</span>
      </p>
      <p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-ink-muted">
        The direct lines — no funnel, no gatekeeper.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        {socials.map((s) => (
          <a href={s.href} target="_blank" rel="noopener me" class="btn btn-secondary">
            <Icon name={socialIcon(s.label)} size={16} />
            {s.label}
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</PageLayout>
